title: 2016+ Flashforge Creator Pro simplified spool holder

description.text:
What do you look for in a spool holder? If it's strength and ease of printing, then this one was designed for you!

I needed a pair of filament spool holders for my Flashforge Creator Pro, and I didn't want to print ones that required generating supports. This design is as simple as they come, uses as little filament as possible, and doesn't require any supports. Infill can be very low at 10% and still be much stronger than other designs.

Due to the nature of designing these without the need for supports, I've created separate left and right .STL files. Determine which one you need by viewing your printer from the front.

description.text:
"Keep it coasty" coaster
A flipping lid coaster to prevent your mug of hot tea/coffee cooling too quickly. Fitted to the Edinburgh ST Microelectronics mug, but feel free to modify it using the solidworks and STL files included (connector .prt is missing - but is very easy to make).

This is a simple print, can be done at a high speed and with both ABS and PLA. I recommend ABS for it's improved insulative and heat resistance properties, and it will be difficult to not get PLA to warp over the lid and perhaps the base. A 20% infill is the standard for my prints.

To construct it all together you need a small elastic band (for the hook to pull down the lever, and pull up the lid), and three 3mm screws, one being at least 20mm in length, the others can be about 12mm or more.

title: Quick change carriage for CTC Prusa i3

description.text:
I bought myself a laser module and needed to a quick change system so I won't have to screw one carriage off and screw the next one on so I after a lot of research I came up with this quick change system. It's easy in use, just slide one off and slide the other one on.
I made it for the CTC Prusa i3 with the alu right angle Z carriage but will probably fit other printers with 8mm rods with LM8UU bearings (hope that's the right number anyway)

I used 15 pin D-sub connectors, wiring is with the pic above

The T shaped thing is a cable holder that I didn't think of when I designed the modified Y carriage so designed and printed it afterward. I glued it on the back of the extruder caddy and cable tied the cables to it, don't use it if you don't want to.

The small cable holder screw to the top of the laser caddy to hold the cables, again, don't use it if you don't want to.

I don't know how to add videos with the pic above so here are the links to two short videos I uploaded to youtube earlier on. Part 1 shows the printer working and Part 2 shows how the caddies are changed.

Part 1: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hnQwVYYEHZc

Part 2: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HuIc9wPnOys&feature=youtu.be

*DESCLAIMER** (probably not needed but I am not taking any chances)

If you intend to print this and use it please make sure you turn your printer off before you pull the caddy off or slide the other one on.

Failing to take this precaution can result in your printer board being damaged and I will not be responsible for it. You use it at your own risk.

If you like it and print it, please give us a like and leave a comment.

Thanks

comments.author: Bronston

comments.text: I don't have the i3 any more, it blew up so I bought myself a Tronxy X3A but I used a piece of 9mm plywood that sat on top of the glass so the laser beam wouldn't damage anything under it. I did it in such a way that it just fitted between the glass holder corners I printed so it would sit at the same place every time and wouldn't move while lasering. This meant that I could home the axis and have the "home" position exactly at the same place all the time.  The only problem using plywood is that it can warp so probably best to get a piece of 2 or 3mm thick alu sheet but you might have to paint it with matt black so it doesn't reflect or better still, a piece of anodised alu should be better, you won't have that problem then and the laser won't/can't damage it.

(note! The stl for the "frame" (or cage) part has been updated to fix a reported problem with fitting at the top between the Ultralight mount's screws and the motor. With the revised "Frame.stl", no sanding should be needed now.) :)

This set is to provide a cooler for use with the 713maker.com Titan Aero ULTRALIGHT Extruder mount, with either a Volcano or E3D V6 hot end, for the Folgertech FT-5 printer. It is designed to be used with a 25mm deep NEMA 17 motor, but there is a spacer to alternately use it with a 20mm deep "pancake" motor. It provides a VERY rigid and lightweight cooling solution using a 50mm x 50mm x 15mm blower fan with a direct path from output to the duct outlets while pulling cool air from the side (instead of from close to the heated bed).

All parts print without supports or rafts (though a cooler or side fan would be needed to print cleanly).

Note that not all 50mm blowers are created equal! I don't know of any of the ball-bearing types that will work with the PWM speed control provided by the MKS board of the FT-5, so unless you want to experiment it might be best to steer clear of those. For other fans, the thing to look for is the current rating -- a 12V 0.06A rated fan will work ok, but its output is pretty wimpy. Look for a 12V 0.14A to 0.16A fan, those seem to move quite a bit more air (you may even need to turn the speed down to 50% or so in some prints!).

File descriptions:

Duct and fan mount for Volcano.stl:  The duct and fan for use with Volcano hot end.
       (note that Repetier reports a "non-Manifold" error for this model, but Meshmixer reports no errors, and Slic3r slices it just fine!). 
Duct and fan mount for std V6.stl: The duct and fan for use with a standard V6 (non-Volcano) hot end.
Frame.stl: A lightweight cage that goes around the motor and provides a mounting surface for the duct and fan
Back plate.stl: A plate that screws onto the back of the frame/cage and and to the back of the motor, providing better support for the frame.
Nozzle Spacer (optional).stl: a spacer to let you lower the fan duct 2mm closer to the print bed if desired.  Most slicers will also let you adjust the thickness of this part if you want.  Using the spacer will put more air on the part and less on the nozzle, but will reduce clearance of the duct from the bed (more likely to run into mirror mounting clips, for example).
Motor spacer (optional) for 20mm pancake: Lets you use a 20mm pancake motor instead of the 25mm pancake motor, for further weight reduction.

Hardware notes:
The screws to hold the plastic back plate to the motor are M3x 25mm (qty 2).
The screws to hold the back plate to the cage/frame are about 9mm long 3mm or #4 sheet metal or self-tap screws (qty 2) (not critical).

The screws that hold the fan to its mount are about M3x25, with M3 nuts of course (I used the M3 Nyloc nuts from the FT-5 build). (qty 2)

The screws that hold the Volcano duct to the cage are 3mm or #4 sheet metal or self-tap screws, one is about 25mm long, the other about 7mm long (1 each). Try to get a FLATHEAD one for the 25mm, so it doesn't stick out far below the duct. The small self-tap screws that hold the plastic back plate to the cage are 3mm or #4 about 9mm long.
For the Standard V6 duct, use an approximately 18mm long self-tap screw for the long one.

(If you want to get fancy, you could tap out the holes at the bottom of the cage for M3 or #4-40 screws, but self-tap seem to work well here at least with PET-G)

File Sources:
The Frame, Backplate, and Spacers are original designs done in Fusion360
The "Duct and fan mount" parts are a very-remixed combination of:
A duct design by 3D Genera: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2332177
A 50mm fan mount design by Onebaldman: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1738499

description.text: Replace two parts in X-axis extension thing 215294 to make use of the increased Y-axis travel of the Y-axis extension thing 229854. Includes built-in bed-leveling adjustment - without springs! (see instructions for details)
PARTS REQUIRED

• 18"x6"x0.025" aluminum sheet (home depot)
  • 28" 0.25x0.25 aluminum bar
  • scotch mounting tape (white, foam-centered double stick tape, home depot)
  • 4 M3x20mm screws
    • TOOLS

• 2.5mm & 8mm drill
  • M3 tap and handle (optional, amazon)
  • heat gun
    • INSTRUCTIONS

NOTE - author has only tested models with KISSlicer

  • print parts - these parts will NOT print on the original simple in the 100x100 configuration. You can print on simple with original bed with X-axis extension thing 215294

  • finish parts by drilling out 8mm and 2.5mm holes. The 2.5mm is the top front hole and the only bottom hole
    • ... following assume you have already installed x-axis thing....

  • lossen belt tensioner, remove bed, then remove all parts from rods - save right end

  • Slide the left end onto the rods. If it doesn't go use heat gun to warm it up enough to go on. Make sure rods are fully inserted.

  • Slide right support onto rods. Again warm to get it to go

  • replace original right end support

  • slide belt into left support. Again warm up and "open" clamp if you need clearance then warm up and squeeze shut with plyers to clamp the belt

  • Thread the front screw through the bed support (top) until it is resting on the rod support (bottom). Put the back screw through the top clearance hole and start in the thread on the bottom but do not tighten

  • cut the aluminum bar so you have two pieces that fit between the left end and the right support

  • notch the back corners of the aluminum sheet as shown in picture to give clearance for the screw heads. Note this thing does NOT print to the edge of the bed so this will not reduce print area

  • apply and trim the double-sided mounting tape to the parts and the bars as shown in the picture, remove top green tap

  • place sheet on parts without bars. The press the bars under the sheet at the edges
    • Leveling the bed

  • move the hotend over the front rod (not the front edge) on the left side of the bed. Set Z to be "just above the bed"

  • move to the back edge of the bed then adjust the front screw to lift the bed to be the same amount of "just above" as previous step. Once you have a position loosely tighten the back screw so that the bed doesn't lift if you push down on the front end

  • repeat for right side

title: Freewheel removal tool FR-1.2 (this doesn't work!)

description.text:
This is my attempt at making an FR-1.2 freewheel removal tool for a bicycle. The model has very accurate dimensions, however the torque required to remove a freewheel is much higher than the shear force of the material.

First attempt was with pla, printed hollow to save on time, and printed in the vertical position. It went into the wheel with a few taps from a hammer. With the application of force, the teeth did not slip, but the material broke. Using a dremel, I removed the remnants from the wheel.

For the second attempt I used ABS and printed in the horizontal orientation for improved strength. I made the model solid for this attempt. I was able to apply a lot more force, however the material still broke.

Conclusion - This tool is not yet feasible with current materials. The torque required to remove a freewheel is too high and requires a tool made from steel. Luckily, the tool can be found for about $5 on ebay. Unfortunately you will have to wait awhile to get it (I was impatient so I tried making my own).

Models include hollow and solid versions of 1" socket and square tools.

title: Elbow joint (snap in, STL and 123d file)

description.text:
hey.
I made this elbow joint in order to integrate it in other pieces, like figurines or some other parts.

It's two 10mm cylinders that are joined by a 90 degree (with one side flat on the male part) or 180 degree joint. Good for elbows and knees for the 90 degree version and for who knows what for the 180 degrees one (the one where the male part is completely rounded).

here is a short vid of the 180 joint: https://youtu.be/VCa5kigsRd0
It looks like it didn't go all the way to 180 but my fingers were in the way; it does do the full 180.

Anyways, the real important part here, I printed about 10 various iterations of this until I got one to work well; I tried different ball sizes (the balls that stick out and snap in the recesses) and they all broke the sides of the female part until this one.

It's probably scalable, I haven't tried it. I'm uploading the 123d file so you can go from there and integrate it into other projets (to open two separate files in the same 123d project, just open one, and then drag the other 123d into the window; it'll ask you to open in current, or create new project.. just open in current....)

This was made with PLA (which is less flexible, which is why you need the right tolerances), printed at .2mm with 10% infill any more infill just makes everything tougher, for extra tough action figures, I guess.

If you like it, LIKE it. or collect it. or both! if you use it for a project, make certain you post a made it... that'd be awesome.

xsize=length

fn_edge_out=edge outside # of segments
fn_edge_in=edge inside # of segments
fn_corner_out=corner outside # of segments
fn_corner_in=corner inside # of segments

All dimensions are in mm.
Fn values are the number of segments in rounded edges and corners. Large values increase smoothness of these elements, but slow rendering. Recommend using fn values shown to start your design.

taught when they are around the base.

Step 3. Attach the top and base together making sure the angle on the top piece is angled
down so the cards slide in easy.

description.text:
Whitney Potter, a.k.a. Shapespeare, a.k.a. cohost of 3D Printing Today Podcast, created an Arduino driven photo capture system for photogrammetry and published an Instructable on how to build your own. You can find all the information on building, wiring, parts, etc in the original post. The parts here will make more sense after reading that post.

This post just contains alternate printed parts and software:

  • a case for the Arduino and LCD
  • a clip to mount the EasyStepper driver board on the Arduino
  • rotating platform for use with Nema 14 or 17 motor
  • modified software

Parts in the picture:

  • Arduino Mega 2560* - The case is designed around the Elegoo version with full size USB port, I'm not sure how much variation there is in these boards. If buying a new one, I'd avoid the boards that require installing unsigned USB drivers.
  • Sainsmart LCD*
  • EasyDriver Stepper Motor Driver*
  • NEMA 14 or 17 motor
  • 3 or more 623ZZ bearings*
  • M3 Screws

Stepper Driver:
See the pictures for how the stepper drivers is mounted, the motor driver pins are mounted to the back side of the board and it's clipped in place.

Case:
The case folds around the LCD and Arduino, and is held together by two short flathead M3 screws. The buttons need to be fairly loose, try scaling them smaller if they're too tight to operate each button independently.

Platform:
The motor platform comes in Nema 14 and Nema 17 sizes (I haven't tried the Nema 17 version. The base and bearings are optional, and are really only needed for heavy objects. It has a dozen bearing mount points to allow for different configurations.

Software:
I switched a couple of the buttons and changed a few other things in the code. The version I modified is included in the scanner_firmware.zip file. I expect to make more changes to the software when I have a chance to do more scanning. The changelog is below:

  • save number of steps to EEPROM when starting a scan
  • swap controls (UP/DOWN for rotation without trigger, RIGHT to change number of steps)
  • display amount of rotation in degrees
  • tweaks to display text
  • fix issue with postWait state not reached
  • fix display refresh / crawl issue
  • refactoring and reformatting

Filaments:
Atomic Filament Ruby Red PETG, Metallic Silver PLA, Pearlescent Blue PLA, Impact Resistant White PLA.

description.text:
This was a quick 1 hour design on request from my father who owns a Telstra Branded ZTE T303 candy bar phone.

Updated 5/5/2017
Added heavy duty lid

It probably has glitches - drop me a comment if you want the source files to mod your own.

You will need:
1 X M3X25mm screw.
1 X M3 nylock nut
2-4 X M3 washers

Requested features of this design:

  • Emergency switch must be obstructed - to prevent continued false triggering.
  • Side switches accessible but "Bump Proof" - they now require slender fingers or a pen
  • Flashlight still functional
  • Docking port contacts must be obstructed - to prevent accidental shorting on keys in pocket
  • Lid or cover in flip-phone style - to prevent accidental emergency calls when locked
  • Rear Speaker port for better sound quality
  • "Grippy texture" - achieved through use of acetone and ABS filament.
  • Robust design for drop resistance.

Always happy to take comments, so please don't hesitate.

description.text:
Antibody Modelling Kit

It is our immune system that keeps us from getting sick. Central to our immune response are proteins known as antibodies. These Y-shaped molecules are custom made by special cells in the body (B-cells) to bind to specific antigens (another name for molecules the immune system recognizes), especially of bacteria and viruses. By binding, antibodies can often neutralize these pathogens and make them easier to find and destroy by our immune cells.

This kit is designed to model the interaction between antibody (also known as immunoglobulin G, or IgG) and antigen (Ag). By inserting magnets, you can stick your models to a magnetic white board, or best of all, simulate antibody binding by floating your models on water.

The models do require some carefully placed magnets (3mm diameter x 1mm height cylindrical neodymium magnets) which you can order in the usual places.

By using the immunoglobulin adapter pieces we can turn the IgG antibody to the IgA (2-fold) and IgM (5-fold) antibody types, or use them with the antigen pieces to build small 'viruses'. (Obviously not to scale!)

This is still very much a work in progress, but hopefully illustrates dynamically some of the basic principles in immune system biology. I am very open to comments and suggestions to improve the model!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qm57pt_rR68&feature=youtu.be

To assemble the model kit properly you will need:

Neodymium disk magnets (3mm diameter x 1mm) -2 for every IgG and 1 for every Ag
3mm drill bit - to help clear the magnet hole.
Modelling glue - to help keep the magnets in place.

Make sure to print the models with minimal infill, - they do need to float after all.

There are two main pieces in the kit which we add magnets to: the IgG (antibody) and the Ag (antigen) models and it is really important that we insert the magnets the right way to get the binding to work! More precisely, the magnet orientations need to be opposite in the Antibody (IgG) to the Antigen (Ag) models. Looking at the underside of the IgG and Ag models there should be holes just big enough to fit the 3mm magnets (see images). (You may need to clean out the holes with the drill bit). Press a magnet into this hole, remembering to keep the orientation the same for the same model piece. It is easier to handle this with a short stack of cylinder magnets, rather than one at a time. Make sure to reverse the orientation of the magnet for the other set. ie) say, have all the magnets with North facing up for the IgG model and North facing down for the Ag model. Don't worry if you mess a few up; there are small holes through the models which you can use a paperclip to poke out the magnets and try again.

Now that the magnets have been inserted, you can slot the IgG and Ag pieces into the various adapters to make larger complexes and start your modelling. Try make some IgA or IgM complexes. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antibody
You can make some viruses by adding Ag pieces to the Virus or IgM adapters.
Make sure the magnets are all facing the same way in the models!

Once you have the magnets sitting correctly you may want to add a spot of modelling glue to keep them there.

Simulating Antibody-Antigen interactions.

To simulate Ab-Ag interactions, fill a small tub with water and carefully place the antibody models with the magnets facing down. These should remain floating apart due to the repulsion of the magnets. A few drops of detergent in the water is handy to help with surface tension effects.

Next add some 'Viruses' with the Ag models on the surface, again with all the magnets facing down. If all goes well, the Antibodies should start sticking to the Antigens on the virus perhaps even sticking some together.

A special thanks to Eleanor and Charlotte, year 10 students who started this project as part of work experience at Melbourne Bioinformatics, Melbourne University.

The underside of the IgG model piece. Inserting the magnet into the underside of the Antigen model piece. Notice the reversed polarity of the magent to the IgG piece!

title: RC airplane Parametric Outrunner Motor Mount

description.text: Updated 08-03-2015 Updated the Scad file to produce rotated output for easier printing. The new Scad file has the suffix rotated to use the new file.
I designed this motor mount to be able to install an oversized PARK480 electric outrunner motor into one of my RC airplanes.

This file is parametric and the mount is able to have all of its facets changed via the variables in the SCAD file.  
The default stick length is 90mm, width is 10mm and the mount plate diameter is 52 mm.  
SCAD file has the ability to minimalize the motor mount plate with cut-outs around the perimeter of the mount plate.
Use the precompiled STL files for quick printing. One STL file has a round mount plate and the other has a scalloped (cut-outs) mount plate.

Download the SCAD file and edit in OpenScad if you wish to customize the motor mount for your specific RC airplane.
  • Modify the Variables at the top of the SCAD file as necessary.
  • Save, Compile and Render your modified configuration.
  • Export as STL to be printed.
    • OR Download one of the STL files if the default dimensions are satisfactory for use in your RC airplane. (parts require rotation) Orient the object with the motor plate facing the print bed, with the stick mount facing upwards.

Print Instructions:
  • Infill: 35%
  • No support required
  • Prints very cleanly in ABS.

To Do: Align your motor (& its optional motor bracket) onto the face of the printed mount face. Mark and drill screw holes to support the hardware supplied with your outrunner motor. Some motors allow for the power wires to run through the hollowed out stick mount. Hot glue or epoxy the mount into the fuselage of your RC airplane. Enjoy!

description.text:

Description

This is an alternative X-Carriage for the popular Voron CoreXY printer (compatible with the 1.0 and 1.5 X/Y gantry, but resembles the look of the 1.5 X-Carriage). For some more detailed shots (of the CAD assembly) see my [Imgur Album][http://imgur.com/a/6rihX].

It has two side fans (35x35x10mm Blower Fans) which heavily improve the part cooling over the original part cooler (which kind of shoveled away some air around the nozzle, but didn't really provide part cooling).

Beware: since I use IR Z-Probes and wanted my E3Dv6 hotend to be unmovable, I removed the ability to use the Nozzle as a Z-Probe. The X-Carriage is designed to be used either with dc42's IR Z-Probe or the compatible Aus3D IR Z-Probe.

Notice: the 35x35x10 Blower Fans are usually driven by 5V. So please keep in mind that you have to provide a 5V source to control these fans.

BOM

Available Parts

  • 1x -- E3Dv6 Hotend (Genuine)
  • 1x -- 30x30x10 Fan (12V/24V)

Required Parts

  • 2x -- 35x35x10 Blower Fan (5V)
  • 1x -- IR Z-Probe (dc42 / Aus3D)
  • Xx -- M3 Nuts (self-locking may work)
  • Xx -- M3xXmm Hex Socket Screw
  • Xx -- M3xXmm Hex Socket Screw
  • Xx -- M3xXmm Hex Socket Screw
  • Xx -- M3xXmm Hex Socket Screw
  • Xx -- M3xXmm Hex Socket Screw
  • Xx -- M3xXmm Hex Socket Screw

Optional Parts

I use Simplify3D for a while now and am very satisfied with it !
But a problem (of my printer) with it is that the calculated estimated time from Simplify and the real time the print takes scatters significantly (my printer Prusa i3 clone usually takes much longer than the estimated time) !

So i decided to record the actual print times and write a short Microsoft excel program which compares the estimated & the real printing times and makes a linear regression function which should calculate the real time a print will need when I put in the estimated time from the slicer.

Also i added the function that excel takes the actual start time and then calculates the "estimated" end time.

Currently I am collecting further data from my prints (the more data the more accurate the program should work).
I know i won't eliminate the time difference to zero because retractions, accelerations etc. are different in every model but i hope i will reach a window of + 15-20 minutes or so.
The measured data is just usable for my specific printer so you have to record your own data from your slicer / printer.

If someone has further improvement thoughts I am happy to hear about it :).
Yes i know, a linear regression at this stage is quite brave ^^.

(because of publishing reasons i added a .stl file called "eisstaberl" which you can forget ^^)

27.6.2017: in version v3 the slope & axis intercept get calculated automatically.
After now 8 measuring points it looks not that bad :)

description.text:
On March 2017, Japanese domestic airplane named YS-11 was retired from about half century service.
YS-11 is equipped the turboprop engine named Rolls Royce "DART".
DART engine series were used Vickers "Viscount744 and 828" and Fokker "F27 Friendship" too in Japan.
Both the models of basic structure and features are the same.
Features of the engine are as follows;
(1) Centrifugal (Impeller type) compressor (2 stages)
(2) Can type Combustion Chamber (7 ea)
(3) Axial Flow Turbine (3 stages)
(4) Reduction gears and propeller shaft (reduction ratio = about 0.1)
(5) Air inlet cowling with Oil Cooler Air Passage

I worked with these engines for long time, therefore I tried to make "Cut-Model" as the memorial model on the desk.
Size and shape of every parts were taken from A4 sized sectional view sheet and some illustrations and pictures at this time.

Download files includes;
-files: STL Files - Sectionalized ZIP
-images: STL File Figure and Index Picture for assembly Aid

-Aluminum Tubes
9mm dia x Appox. 70mm - as Compressor Rotor Shaft (Make slots both ends)
6mm dia x Appox. 100mm - as Turbine to Compressor Coupling Shaft

-Screws
Micro screws M1.4x3L - Appox. 70 ea - Direct screw-in to 1 mm dia hole (No nut),
Head side flange hole is 1.5 mm dia.
Screws M2 x 20L - 1ea - M2 Tap is used - Starter associate parts
Screws M2 x 10L - Appox. 12ea - M2 Tap is used - Red. Gear Panels associate parts and IGV
Screws M2 x 6L - Appox. 4ea - M2 Tap is used - Diffusers and Turb. Shaft Coupling

Assembly Points

  • Rotors, Gear Train Set and Casings can be assembled and adjusted separately.
  • Combustion Air Casing is slid to the outlet elbow assembly until aft end clears from the turbine case its bore at first. Then slide back to bore. Gluing is optional.
  • Standard Skill (such as Drilling, Tapping, Filing, Tightening, Painting and Gluing etc) is needed and perseverance too.

description.text: Someone on the replicator google group mentioned they wanted more cooling for their MB. I think it might be overkill but here it is.

I just added an stl version of the fan mount so you don't need a laser cutter to make that part. You can use a hand saw of jigsaw if you want to cut the holes for the main cover.
This is designed to force air in from the front & back left side of the replicator and exhaust it in the center towards the right side. 
I Added an additional 40mm fan mount on the cable pass thru support. I also make the cable pass thru considerably smaller to restrict airflow yet still allow cables to pass thru.
I made 2 intake ports on the front and back to bring in cool air.
I soften up the corner where the extruder assembly exits to make it easier to take on and off the cover.
I simplified the finger hole and added a second to also make it easier to remove.
I also corrected the nut retainer on the cable pass since it was off in the orginal design from the bolt hole position on the shipping model.

This card and dice holder replaces the original one from Zombicide (Season 1).

Printing:

Card Sizing Note:

When measuring cards for this model, I noticed the size of the Zombicide cards varied by around 0.4mm between the base game and expansions. I sized the model to fit my largest cards, but if you find that you have cards that don't fit, please let me know and I can resize the model.

description.text:
This is a 60mm Square-1 I designed using OnShape. Please feel free to use the files in order to print yourself one of those puzzles.

For a functioning puzzle print those parts (in PLA plastic):

  • 2 x "Core"
  • 8 x "Corner"
  • 8 x "Edge"

In addition you'll need 1 screw (M3, about 20mm long) and a suitable nut. For a better finish you'll also need some way to create stickers. Using sandpaper and silicone oil on the printed pieces is recommended.

I wish you fun with this puzzle. Please contact me if you have any questions.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

I'd suggest to turn the pieces so that they are laying flat on the build plate. If you want to decrease the amount of work on this project, you can also use a higher resolution. 0.3mm is a fast version which turned out to work just fine on my printer. Due to the big pieces I didn't even use any adheasion help in the slicer. Using hairspray on a heated build plate (60°C) was enough.

Assembly and Post-Processing

Sanding is optional on this puzzle but I'd really recommend to do so. Using 80 Grid snadpaper and continuing down to something like 320 Grid can improve the moving significatly as it reduces the friction. I'd also suggest to add lubrican or silicone oil to make it move better.

In order to make this a functional puzzle, I designed it so that it uses a screw and a nut. Of course you could just print a stick of about 3-4mm diameter and insert it + glue it down but I figured it would be better to use a screw. I used a M3 20mm one with the suitable nut.

Insert the pie-pieces (alternating a small and a big one) in the middle pieces. Then put the middle pieces together and screw in the screw. If you want to, you can also use a spring which improves the turning quality. In case you don't have a nut that holds in place, just glue it down with hot-glue so that the screw can't get loose anymore. I also used the hotglue to cover the screw-holes. Please note that stickering is essential for a good-looking finish here!

Once you managed to get the puzzle working so that the middle slice rotates freely without getting loose, you can sticker the puzzle up using Venyl-stickers. I cut them myself. As an alterantive, filling the holes and spray-painting the puzzle could be an alternative which would result in a single-colour puzzle which is easier to solve.

comments.text: Probably a M3 nut. You need one that fits your screw. If you can't find one you can also use hot glue to fix the screw. That is not the best way and you won't be able to change the tension afterwards but if that's all you have it will work. I used a M3 screw (at least 20mm long) with the corresponding nut.
